    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <p class="section-sub">Common questions about S&P 500 concentration</p>
    <div class="faq-list" id="faq-list"></div>
  </div>

  <!-- Methodology -->
  <div class="methodology">
    <h3>Methodology</h3>
    <p>This study analyzes the market capitalization concentration of the S&P 500 index as of March 2026.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Constituent weights</strong> sourced from SlickCharts.com, which derives data from the S&P Dow Jones Indices.</li>
      <li><strong>Financial metrics</strong> (sector, P/E ratio, market cap) enriched via Finviz screener for all 501+ constituents.</li>
      <li><strong>Concentration metrics</strong> computed as cumulative weight of top N stocks (top 5, 10, 20, 50).</li>
      <li><strong>Sector breakdown</strong> uses Finviz sector classifications (similar to GICS).</li>
      <li>Data represents a point-in-time snapshot. Weights change daily as prices move.</li>
      <li>Some dual-class stocks (e.g., GOOGL/GOOG) appear as separate entries per index methodology.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- Citation -->
  <div class="citation">
    <h3>Cite This Research</h3>
    <code>Westmount Research. "S&P 500 Market Cap Concentration 2026: How Top-Heavy Is the Index?" westmountfundamentals.com/market-concentration. Published March 9, 2026.</code>
  </div>
